Problem 1

Using the bisection method calculate at least one zero for $f(x) = −x^3 + 4x^2 − 2 $starting for a suitable initial guess. You may want to reuse the code provided in the exercise session.

The NLRoot package, which implements several methods (e.g., secant method), also contains a function for finding the root of a function with the bisection method.

#install.packages("NLRoot")
library(NLRoot)

We wish to find the root of the function

\(f(x) = −x^3 + 4x^2 − 2\)

Now we plot the function to find an interval containing the root.

func <- function(x) {
- x^3 + 4 * x^2 - 2
}
curve(func, xlim=c(-3,3), col='blue', lwd=1.5, lty=2)
abline(h=0)
abline(v=0)

We have two roots in the range [-1,1].

BFfzero(func, -1, 1)
## [1] 1
## [1] -0.6554413
## [1] -7.168402e-06
## [1] 2
## [1] 0.7892426
## [1] -6.958254e-06
## [1] "finding root is successful"

Installing GenSA

#install.packages("GenSA")
library(GenSA)
  • Search for the first minimum
res <- GenSA(par=-20, fn=func2, lower=-20, upper=-18, control=list(maxit=10000, temperature=10))
res[c("value", "par")]
## $value
## [1] 1.113729e-22
## 
## $par
## [1] -18.95494
